snippet.textDisplay:
Doug can you stop calling Liftbacks "hatchbacks" (12:31). I'm not even a car guy and this bothers me. If it has a fastback tail end with a hatch instead of a trunk, then it's a liftback. Same goes for the Kia Stinger, Tesla Model S, plenty of small sporty cars throughout the years (i.e. Integra/RSX, Celica). Yes, a liftback is technically a hatchback, but the body style is significantly different.

I'm sorry to complain but anytime a car has this you seem to mention it as if it's some kind of oddity, almost an affront, when it's actually a pretty practical and aesthetically attractive design choice (which I think you've mentioned on at least one occasion). Honestly, if we're going to stave off the homogenization of cars into crossovers, we need more liftbacks on the market.

snippet.textDisplay: I bought my 2011 Panamera S last year and stepping up to a Porsche from a VW I can tell you that you will be more than pleased with this car. Mine is black on black and looks new (38K miles)and folks do think you spent 100K. If you do consider this car make sure the recall items have been fixed along with the thermostat housing (especially the thermostat housing) as it has (2) hard lines that were epoxied into the housing and will fail and if you are doing 110 you will probably lose the engine. The car drives great and glides at 130 mph and loves to corner even at it's size. Best part is the depreciation slows down substantially around the 30K mark. There are some YouTube guys out there that will show you how to maintain it yourself making it more than affordable.

snippet.textDisplay: I really like my wife's 2013 Panamera S. It's 4.0 liter V8 is the near perfect power plant for this model.  The extra hp turns the Panamera into a real sportscar.  I test drove the V6 and found it to be so weak as to make  the entire driving experience rather boring.  The V8 significantly enlivens the experience.  As you say, the car is extremely well made and reflects the care one expects from this marque.  Maintenance and fuel expenses are surprisingly low.  For example, all-in expenses (per mile) are nearly identical to my Audi A3.  Unbelievable but true.  While the body looks a little ungainly, the added cargo space thoroughly offsets this disadvantage.  With respect to the other disadvantage you cite, the car is big but it's incredibly light (thanks to space age materials).   All in all, we're very pleased with our big baby.  Indeed, I've become a Porsche fanboy as a result of my ownership experience.  It's terrific to have and drive a car made by people who genuinely care about their product and who honor their sporting/racing tradition in every vehicle they build (the tach is the centerpiece gauge).   I give my car a 75-80 on your scale.  I don't disagree with your score; the V8 makes that much difference.
